# Adversary fixture: FM2-N3 — Quoted formula `{ }` graph-scoping
#
# Hypothesis: In N3, a quoted formula `{ <s> <p> <o> }` introduces a formula
# (named graph / cited graph) whose triples are NOT asserted in the default
# graph — they are nested inside the formula and only become part of the
# ambient graph when the formula itself is the object of an outer triple (or
# used in a rule conclusion). A parser that "flattens" the quoted formula
# and emits `<s> <p> <o>` into the default graph has misread the semantics.
#
# This fixture:
#   1. Declares a formula value as the object of an outer triple.
#   2. Verifies that the parser emits exactly ONE triple in the default graph
#      (the outer triple whose object is the formula), not THREE.
#   3. A parser that leaks the inner triples to the default graph would emit
#      four triples (1 outer + 3 inner), producing an ObjectMismatch or
#      extra-fact divergence against a conformant parser.
#
# N3 spec §4: A quoted formula `{ ... }` is a first-class node; the triples
# within it are "cited" — they describe content of the formula, not the
# ambient graph.
#
# Expected: parse succeeds; exactly 1 fact in the default graph.
# Divergence signal: ExtraFactIn — parsers that flatten quoted formulas emit
# 4 facts instead of 1.
#
# Spec: W3C N3 Team Submission 2011-03-28 §4 — Formulae.

@prefix ex:  <http://example.org/> .
@prefix log: <http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/log#> .

ex:doc log:content { ex:Alice ex:knows ex:Bob . ex:Bob ex:name "Bob" . ex:Alice ex:age 30 . } .
